// Adversarial regression fixtures — defend the structural advantage of the
// MCP corpus over generic web-summary answers. Every case here exercises a
// footnote, asterisk, line item, structured field, or graph edge that a
// page-summarizing LLM (e.g. ChatGPT without this MCP) is empirically known
// to drop. If any case regresses, the moat narrowed — investigate before
// merging.
//
// Every expected value was confirmed against the live MCP on 2026-05-18
// (corpus snapshots: 2026-05-13T16:48:28.947Z for policies/calendars,
// 2026-05-18T14:35:16.534Z for online/tuition/emergency/courses).
// Corpus-rule-clean — no training-data fallback.
//
// Dispatched by `tool` field. Assertion type determined by `kind`. Threshold
// is 100%: even one regression should fail the suite.
//
// SCOPE: only deterministic tools (online, emergency, tuition, courses) are
// covered here so this suite can be CI-gated. The analogous moat cases for
// chain_find_relevant_policies (e.g. "grade appeal → AOP 13.14") and
// find_msu_date (e.g. "Fall 2026 finals = 2026-12-03 to 2026-12-10") live in
// the dates suite + the policies questions.jsonl — those tools live-scrape
// MSU from the stdio bundle and are too flaky for CI. Run them manually
// before each release via `npm run eval -- --suite dates` /
// `npm run eval -- --suite policies`.
